<paragraph blockId="94.[151,1436,1157,1221]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,281,1157,1184]" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Status.</emphasis>
Because of its crepuscular habits, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[671,782,1158,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Tholymis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tillarga">
<emphasis box="[671,782,1158,1184]" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">T. tillarga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easy to miss, but it is much more common than records suggest. We rank it NT.
</paragraph>
